\section*{Development/types of Hb}
- Embryonic Hb:predominates wks.4-8, disappear by the $3{ }^{\text {rd }}$ month

Gower 1: $\zeta_{2} \varepsilon_{2}$
Gower 2: $\alpha_{2} \quad \varepsilon_{2}$
Portland: $\zeta_{2} \quad \gamma_{2}$
- The zeta $(\zeta)$ chains are structurally similar to alpha chains

\section*{Fetal Hb}
- Contains $\alpha_{2} \gamma_{2}$
- Predominates by the $10-11^{\text {th }}$ wk, by $24^{\text {th }}$ wk it constitutes 90\%, declines in $3^{\text {rd }}$ trimester :makes 70\% of Hb at birth.Synthesis declines rapidly postnatally only traces found by 6-12 mo.
- Adults have less than $2 \%$ fetal Hb
- Its heterogeneous coz the $\gamma$ chain synthesis is directed by 2 sets of genes.Chains differ at position 136 in presence of either glycine or alanine.ratio at birth 3:1

\section*{Adult Hb}
- $\mathrm{Hb} \mathrm{A} \mathrm{A}_{1}: \alpha_{2} \beta_{2}$
- $\mathrm{Hb} \mathrm{A} 2: \alpha_{2} \delta_{2}$
- $\mathrm{Hb} \mathrm{A} \mathrm{A}_{1}$ makes $5-10 \%$ of the total by wk 24. At term $30 \%$, by $6-12 \mathrm{mo}$. The adult pattern appears.
- $\mathrm{Hb} \mathrm{A}_{2}$ makes $2-3 \%$
- Ratio of $\mathrm{A}_{1}: \mathrm{A}_{2}=30: 1$
- Alpa chains 141 AA, beta 146AA

\section*{Alterations of Hb by disease}
- Gower found in trisomy $13 / 15$
- Portland found in stillborn infants with homozygous a thalassemia
- Hb F elevation occurs with haematologic stress
- $\mathrm{HbA}_{2}$ elevated in beta thal., vit. $\mathrm{B}_{12}$ def. and folate def. Decreased levels in Fe. Def. and alpha thal.

\section*{Genetics}
- Alpha like chains encoded by two sets of genes on Ch. 16
- Beta,gamma and delta chains encoded by genes on Ch. 11

\section*{Classification of hemoglobinopathies}
- Structural ;mutation of amino acids of globin chain leading to abn.polymerization, altered solubility and O2 binding
- Thalassemia syndromes:impaired prdn. of globin chains
- Thalassemia hemoglobin variants: combine features of thal. and structural Hbpathies

\section*{Cotd}
- Hereditary persistence of fetal Hb (HPFH)
- Acquired Hbpathies: modification of Hb molecule by toxins eg.methemoglobinaemia

\section*{Epidemiology}

The disease is common in Africa, Middle east, Mediterranean countries and in India.
- In the US the disease is common among the blacks with $8 \%$ of them being carriers and $0.8 \%$ being homozygous
- In Kenya SCD is common among the Luo(53.4\%) and Luhyia(24.2\%) tribes in western Kenya and among the Miji Kenda(18.7\%) at the coast.

\section*{Cotd}
- Other tribes including the Kisii's and the Kamba's have been found to have the disease
- The sickle cell trait however has been found in nearly all the tribes of Kenya with the Miji Kenda leading at 35\%
- There are no significant differences between the males and females
- Majority of the cases are between 1-20 years of age
- 2003:26\% of Kenyans in malaria holoendemic regions had the sickle cell genotype opposed to only $3 \%$ in the highland regions

