\section*{History}
- $1^{\text {st }}$ described by Herrick in 1910
- Syndenstericker described the first paediatrics case. He recognized that it's a hemolytic dse.
- 1949-Pauling identified it as an autosomal disorder
- 1959-Ingram described the substitution of valine for glutamate
- Was the $1^{\text {st }}$ dse to be described to be due to molecular mutation

\section*{Pathophysiology}
- Basic defect:Replacement of glutamate by valine at position 6 of the beta globin chain
- The clinical presentation is due to either of these main pathophysiologic processes
vaso-occlusion
hemolysis
Infections

\section*{Molecular pathogenesis}
- The presence of valine at position 6 creates a hydrophobic chain that also has a high propensity of binding with other globin chains
- This leads to interaction btwn. different Hb molecules leading to aggregation into large polymers.
- The polymerization is the $1^{\circ}$ event that leads to distortion of shape and decreased deformability of the cells

\section*{Cotd.}
- The formation of a single nucleus of aggregated molecules is followed by growth and alignment of fibers
- Distortion of shape follows leading to disturbance of structure and function of the membranes

\section*{Rate /Extent of polymer formation depends on:}
- Degree and rate of deoxygenation
- Hb conc.
- Intracellular Hb type.
- pH
- Temperature
- Extacellular osmolarity
